https://www.medianama.com/2024/12/223-rbi-announces-members-committee-develop-responsible-ai-framework/,,RBI Unveils Committee to Shape Responsible AI Guidelines,20241226T164500Z,https://www.medianama.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/RBI-India-recurring-payments-1000x600-1.jpeg,medianama.com,English,India,XLF,Financial,financial sector,"The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has announced the composition of the committee to develop a Framework for Responsible and Ethical Enablement of Artificial Intelligence (FREE-AI) in the Financial Sector, on December 26. The nation‚Äôs central bank had announced the committee on December 6 as part of its Statement on Developmental and Regulatory Policies. While the bank noted that Artificial Intelligence (AI) had the potential to automate complex processes and improve efficiency, it came with risks like algorithmic bias and data privacy. ‚ÄúTo harness the benefits, it is critical to address the attendant risks early in the adoption cycle,‚Äù said the RBI. Accordingly, the committee was set up to ‚Äúrecommend a robust, comprehensive, and adaptable AI framework for the financial sector.‚Äù The committee would include the following members: Dr. Pushpak Bhattacharyya, Professor, Department of Computer Science and Engineering, IIT Bombay (Chairperson) Ms. Debjani Ghosh, Distinguished Fellow, NITI Aayog; Independent Director, Reserve Bank Innovation Hub; and Ex-President, NASSCOM Dr. Balaraman Ravindran, Professor and Head, Wadhwani School of Data Science and AI, IIT Madras Abhishek Singh, Additional Secretary, Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology, Government of India Rahul Matthan, Partner, Trilegal Member Anjani Rathor, Group Head and Chief Digital Experience Officer, HDFC Bank Ltd. Sree Hari Nagaralu, Head of Security AI Research, Microsoft India (R&D) Suvendu Pati, CGM, FinTech Department, Reserve Bank of India (Member Secretary) The terms of reference for the committee are: To assess the current level of adoption of AI in financial services, globally and in India. To review regulatory and supervisory approaches on AI with focus on financial sector globally. To identify potential risks associated with AI, if any and recommend an evaluation, mitigation and monitoring framework and consequent compliance requirements for financial institutions, including banks, NBFCs, FinTechs, PSOs, etc. To recommend a framework including governance aspects for responsible, ethical adoption of AI models / applications in the Indian financial sector. Any other matter related to AI in the Indian financial sector. Background: This development comes as the government is moving to regulate AI with greater scrutiny, especially in the financial sector. The Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) recently informed Regulated Entities (RE) that they would be fully responsible for any AI programs the develop or deploy, including data privacy, compliance with existing laws and even the output of such models. The agency had previously asked Investment Advisers and Research Analysts who used AI tools to reveal the extent of the usage to clients. The Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology (MeitY) has also opened a second round of bids for projects under the ‚ÄúSafe & Trusted AI‚Äù pillar of the government‚Äôs IndiaAI mission. This is after it selected eight proposals during the first round. Also Read: Advertisements How should liability be distributed between different players of the AI ecosystem? #Nama Private banks lead in AI adoption, but public sector catching up, says RBI study A Critique of RBI Governor Shaktikanta Das‚Äô Comments on AI and Big Tech Dominance Risks Support our journalism: For You Sign up for our Daily Newsletter to receive regular updates Stay informed about MediaNama events Have something to tell us? Leave an Anonymous Tip Ask us to File an RTI Sponsor a MediaNama Event"
https://moneylife.in/article/rbi-sets-up-8member-committee-on-ethical-use-of-ai-in-financial-sector/75962.html,,RBI Sets Up 8 - member Committee on Ethical Use of AI in Financial Sector,20241226T161500Z,https://moneylife.in/media/uploads/article/responsive/AI261224.jpg,moneylife.in,English,India,XLF,Financial,financial sector,"slider html RBI Sets Up 8-member Committee on Ethical Use of AI in Financial Sector Moneylife Digital Team 26 December 2024 0 To bookmark you need to sign in Economy & Nation The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) announced the setting up of an eight-member committee to develop a framework for responsible and ethical enablement of artificial intelligence (FREE-AI) in the financial sector. In the December monetary policy review, RBI's former governor Shaktikanta Das mentioned setting up the committee on FREE-AI , especially looking at the rapid transformation in the financial sector enabled by technologies such as AI, tokenisation, and cloud computing. The FREE-AI committee will be headed by professor Pushpak Bhattacharyya from the department of computer science and engineering at Indian Institute of Technology, Bombay (IIT-B). The committee will assess the current level of adoption of AI in financial services globally and in India. Other members in the committee include Debjani Ghosh (distinguished fellow of the NITI Aayog and independent director of Reserve Bank Innovation Hub), Dr Balaraman Ravindran (professor and head, Wadhwani School of Data Science and AI, IIT Madras), Abhishek Singh, (additional secretary in the Union ministry of electronics and information technology-MeitY), Rahul Matthan (Partner at Trilegal), Anjani Rathor (group head and chief digital experience officer of HDFC Bank Ltd), and Sree Hari Nagaralu ( head of security for AI research at Microsoft India (R&D)). Suvendu Pati, the chief general manager (CGM) in RBI's financial technology (fintech) department, is the member secretary of the committee. The committee on FREE-AI will also review regulatory and supervisory approaches to AI, focusing on the global financial sector. It is tasked with identifying potential risks associated with AI and recommending an evaluation, mitigation and monitoring framework and consequent compliance requirements for financial institutions, including banks, non-banking financial companies (NBFCs), fintechs and payment system operators (PSOs). The committee will also recommend a framework that includes governance aspects for the responsible and ethical adoption of AI models and applications in the Indian financial sector. Comments User Alert me when a new comment is posted EDITORS' PICKS MOST POPULAR MOST READ The Great Mumbai Land Grab: How Public Assets Are Being Sold to Private... Explosive: Rs1.5 Lakh Crore+ of Govt, Welfare, Charitable Funds Locked... US Markets: The Age of Artificial Exuberance Motor Insurance Premium: Are you Getting a Fair Deal? From Haridas Mundhra to Adani: How LIC‚Äôs Culture of Secrecy Has Come Full... Justice on Camera: How Openness Is Testing Judicial Conduct Tata Group Grapples with Succession and Power: Will The Legacy Survive? The Elusive Private Capex Boom Unclaimed Wealth: Will the Government‚Äôs New Drive Really Return People‚Äôs... Taxman or SEBI: Who Will Eventually Police Corporate Brand Royalty Payments? Trump H-Visa Bomb, a Blessing in Disguise? Lower Public Float: A Boon for Companies; Threat to Investors Valued Epistemics under Fire: Ex-staff Allege Salaries Withheld and PF... India‚Äôs US$3.9bn Plan To Support Adani Using LIC‚Äôs Funds: Washington... Why Is Bank of Maharashtra Moving Out of Its Own Home? Questions Mount over... Supreme Court Restores Landlord‚Äôs Right, Orders Eviction of Tenants after... From Haridas Mundhra to Adani: How LIC‚Äôs Culture of Secrecy Has Come Full... Rahul Gandhi Says Haryana Election Was ‚ÄòStolen‚Äô through 25 Lakh Fake Voters,... Justice on Camera: How Openness Is Testing Judicial Conduct From Mundhra to Mundra: Recounting a 7-deca